  "prompt": "How can I stop Outlook from synchronising folders automatically?",
  "response": "The method to stop Outlook from automatically synchronizing folders depends on the type of email account you have configured (e.g., Exchange, IMAP, POP3).  Here's a breakdown for each type, along with general tips:\n\n**Important Note:**  Completely stopping all synchronization might not be desirable. It means you won't get new emails, updated calendar events, or changes to your contacts.  Think carefully about whether you truly want to *stop* syncing or just control *when* it syncs.\n\n**1. Exchange Accounts (Microsoft 365, Outlook.com, corporate email):**\n\n*   **Online Mode (Recommended for most users):** With Exchange accounts, Outlook usually runs in Online Mode by default. This means changes are reflected in real-time. While you can't completely stop the constant syncing, you can work offline (see below).\n\n*   **Cached Exchange Mode:** If you are in Cached Exchange Mode (which is common), Outlook keeps a local copy of your mailbox.  You can still work offline and changes will sync when you reconnect.\n\n    *   **How to Check if you're in Cached Exchange Mode:**\n        1.  Go to **File > Account Settings > Account Settings**.\n        2.  Select your Exchange account.\n        3.  The details should show if Cached Exchange Mode is enabled.\n\n    *   **Disabling Cached Exchange Mode (Not Recommended):**\n        1.  **File > Account Settings > Account Settings.**\n        2.  Select your Exchange account.\n        3.  Click **Change**.\n        4.  Uncheck the box labeled \"**Use Cached Exchange Mode to download email to an Outlook data file**\".\n        5.  Restart Outlook.\n\n        **Warning:**  Disabling Cached Exchange Mode will make Outlook much slower, especially if you have a large mailbox. It relies on a constant connection to the server and can be very frustrating.  It's generally *not* recommended unless you have a compelling reason.\n\n*   **Working Offline (General Solution):** The easiest way to temporarily stop syncing with an Exchange account (or any account) is to put Outlook into \"Work Offline\" mode:\n\n    1.  Click the **Send/Receive** tab in the ribbon.\n    2.  Click the **Work Offline** button.  The button will be highlighted when you are offline.\n\n    When you are offline, Outlook won't connect to the server and won't sync. To re-enable syncing, simply click the **Work Offline** button again.\n\n*   **Delaying Send/Receive for Exchange Accounts:**\n    1.  Go to **File > Options > Advanced**.\n    2.  In the **Send and receive** section, uncheck \"**Send immediately when connected**\".\n    3.  Click the **Send/Receive...** button.\n    4.  Under \"**Settings for all Accounts**\", change the \"**Schedule an automatic send/receive every**\" value to a larger number of minutes (e.g., 60 minutes for once an hour) or uncheck it completely to disable automatic send/receive.  You'll then have to manually click \"Send/Receive All Folders\" to sync.\n\n**2. IMAP Accounts:**\n\n*   **Work Offline:**  Similar to Exchange, the simplest way to stop IMAP syncing is to use the **Work Offline** button on the **Send/Receive** tab.\n\n*   **Delaying Send/Receive for IMAP Accounts:**  The same steps for Exchange apply here:\n    1.  Go to **File > Options > Advanced**.\n    2.  In the **Send and receive** section, uncheck \"**Send immediately when connected**\".\n    3.  Click the **Send/Receive...** button.\n    4.  Under \"**Settings for all Accounts**\", change the \"**Schedule an automatic send/receive every**\" value or uncheck it to disable automatic send/receive.\n\n*   **Unsubscribe from IMAP Folders:** IMAP accounts sync all subscribed folders. You can reduce the amount of data synced by unsubscribing from folders you don't need:\n    1.  Right-click on the IMAP account name in the folder pane.\n    2.  Choose **IMAP Folders...**\n    3.  Click the **Query** button to see all folders.\n    4.  Uncheck the boxes next to the folders you want to unsubscribe from.  These folders will no longer be synced.  (You can always re-subscribe later.)\n\n**3. POP3 Accounts:**\n\n*   POP3 accounts, by default, download emails from the server and usually delete them from the server (although you can configure it to leave a copy).  They don't sync folders in the same way as Exchange or IMAP.\n\n*   **Delaying Send/Receive for POP3 Accounts:** Use the same method as IMAP and Exchange:\n    1.  Go to **File > Options > Advanced**.\n    2.  In the **Send and receive** section, uncheck \"**Send immediately when connected**\".\n    3.  Click the **Send/Receive...** button.\n    4.  Under \"**Settings for all Accounts**\", change the \"**Schedule an automatic send/receive every**\" value or uncheck it to disable automatic send/receive.\n\n*   **Manually Check for New Mail:** If you disable automatic send/receive, you'll need to click the **Send/Receive All Folders** button in the **Send/Receive** tab to check for new mail.\n\n**General Tips & Considerations:**\n\n*   **Send/Receive Groups:** In the Send/Receive settings, you can define different \"Send/Receive Groups\" to control which accounts are synced at what interval.  This is a more advanced option for customizing syncing behavior.\n\n*   **Email Size:** If you're concerned about data usage or slow syncing, try to keep your emails as small as possible.  Avoid sending large attachments; instead, use cloud storage services like OneDrive, Google Drive, or Dropbox and share links.\n\n*   **Outlook Mobile App:** If you're mainly concerned about syncing on your desktop Outlook, consider using the Outlook mobile app. You can configure it to sync less frequently or only sync when on Wi-Fi.\n\n*   **Large Mailboxes:** Very large mailboxes (especially with Exchange accounts) can take a long time to sync initially and can consume a lot of resources.  Archiving old emails to a separate PST file can help improve performance.\n\n*   **Check Your Internet Connection:** A slow or unstable internet connection can make syncing seem like it's constantly happening. Make sure you have a reliable connection.\n\n*   **Restart Outlook and Your Computer:** Sometimes, a simple restart can resolve syncing issues.\n\n**In summary:**\n\n*   For **temporary** stopping of syncing, use the **Work Offline** button.  This is the simplest and often best solution.\n*   For **permanently** changing sync frequency, adjust the **Send/Receive** settings in Outlook Options > Advanced.\n*   Disabling **Cached Exchange Mode** is generally **not recommended** for Exchange accounts.\n*   For **IMAP**, consider **unsubscribing** from unnecessary folders.\n\nBefore making any changes, consider why you want to stop synchronization.  If it's due to slow performance or data usage, addressing those underlying issues might be a better long-term solution.  Remember to test any changes you make to ensure they don't negatively impact your workflow.\n",
